Note that many of these symbols have subscript x. It is not necessary to use subscripts when it is understood that the motion is along one of the Cartesian axis. Therefore, we will often write them without verbose symbols: use a, v_0, v, x, t in place of a_x, v_{i,x}, v_{f,x}, \Delta x, \Delta t, respectively. Then, these equations look a lot simpler and remember them in this notation. Actually, you need to remember only the last two for solving problems, but remembering the first also often helps.

	 \amp v = v_0 + a t. \ \ \text{(** to memorize **)}
	 \amp x = v_{av} t.
	 \amp v_{av} = \dfrac{v_{0} + v}{2}.
	 \amp  x = v_{0} t + \dfrac{1}{2}a  t^2. \ \ \text{(** to memorize **)}
	 \amp  v^2 = v_{0}^2 + 2 a  x. \ \ \text{(** to memorize **)}


	 \amp |v_f| = |v_i| = v_{s}  
	 \amp  d = v_{s} \, \Delta t

This says nothing about the acceleration since constant speed only says that absolute value of velocity is constant, but nothing about the direction of the velocity. Without the direction information about velocity, it is impossible to say anything about the acceleration, which depends on change in both magnitude and direction of velocity.
